05:48.880 --> 05:52.760
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:08.340 --> 06:13.620
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:16.260 --> 06:17.960
And here are your hosts.

06:22.760 --> 06:31.560
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Norman Spinrad's best-known novel may be Bug
Jack Barron, a book which has stirred controversy in both England and America. It

06:31.560 --> 06:39.120
was published in this country in 1969, and it's a different sort of science
fiction novel. It's a good example of new-wave science fiction. Character and

06:39.120 --> 06:46.920
style are important, and it deals with social issues such as racism, the
establishment, drugs, the power of the media, and radical protests. There is

06:46.920 --> 06:53.640
also a good deal of sex and violence in the book, and the language is highly
colored. But Spinrad thinks the plot of the book conforms to traditional science

06:53.640 --> 07:03.420
fiction formulas. Actually, what I was trying to do in a way, the book has a
very traditional plot. As far as I was concerned, it has a positive hero, it has

07:03.420 --> 07:12.880
a negative villain. The hero wins, the villain loses, all that stuff that is
considered the traditional way of plotting a book. And yet it's written in a

07:12.880 --> 07:22.780
different kind of way. It kind of takes that superficial kind of plot and treats
it in a realistic manner. The protagonist, Jack Barron, is a powerfully

07:22.780 --> 07:30.920
influential television star who has a talk show watched by 100 million people.
He uses the show as a battlefield to oppose corrupt elements of society. Spinrad

07:30.920 --> 07:37.280
comments on Barron's use of power. The book is about power.

07:37.640 --> 07:48.300
It's about power itself is neutral as far as I'm concerned. It's what people do
with it that counts. Barron is a guy who likes power. He keeps referring to it

07:48.300 --> 07:58.260
as a drug and knows that he can become addicted to it. And for that reason, has
decided to stay away from it. Then he gets drawn back into playing with power

07:58.260 --> 08:07.140
because he comes to the conclusion that it's better for somebody who feels that
way about power to be wielding it than people who don't have any self

08:07.140 --> 08:17.040
-consciousness about the dangers of wielding power. So in that sense, it's a
comment on the power of the media, but it's also a comment on the morality of

08:17.040 --> 08:28.640
power, on the paradox of power, which is that if you leave power to be wielded
by people who do not see the dangers, the personal dangers, the psychological

08:28.640 --> 08:38.540
dangers of being involved with it, then you end up with people like Benedict
Howard, Ronald Reagan, and Richard Nixon who do not have self-consciousness

08:38.540 --> 08:46.920
about the personal dangers, the moral dangers of chasing after power, whereas
somebody like Barron, who is certainly an imperfect person, as all people are,

08:47.580 --> 09:00.120
at least his saving grace, if he has one, is that he is well aware of the
personal dangers of being involved in a quest for power. When Spinrad tried to

09:00.120 --> 09:06.900
get the novel published in this country, he was unsuccessful, so he tried in
Britain. But there was an outcry in Parliament against the book. He relates the

09:06.900 --> 09:16.220
story for us. That novel had a lot of trouble. It was written under contract to
Doubleday, who then rejected it. You have to remember the political climate of

09:16.220 --> 09:26.100
the era. They didn't reject it. They said, we'll publish it if you cut out all
the sex, all the swear words, and all the politics, which was the whole book. So

09:26.100 --> 09:33.800
it took a long time to resell that book here. In the meantime, I took it to
Milford, to a Milford conference, and Mike Moorcock was there. He read it, and

09:33.800 --> 09:42.880
he liked it, and he serialized it in New World. So his first publication was
actually in England, in a magazine. Now, halfway through the serialization, I

09:42.880 --> 09:51.720
forget exactly which part, part three, part four, W.H. Smith, which was the
biggest distribute, still is the biggest distributor in England, refused to

09:51.720 --> 09:59.060
distribute the magazine because of the book in it. Now, at that time, New World
had an Arts Council grant. The Arts Council was an organ of the British

09:59.060 --> 10:09.080
government. Now, the Arts Council supported the magazine against Smith publicly.
And so the flap in Parliament arose when certain right-wing members of

10:09.080 --> 10:17.820
Parliament were aghast that an organ of the British government, the Arts
Council, was defending this kind of stuff. And that's how it became a

10:17.820 --> 10:26.940
parliamentary issue. Bug Jack Barron is being made into a movie with a screenplay
by Harlan Ellison and direction by radical filmmaker Costa-Gavras. It should be

10:26.940 --> 10:29.680
interesting. More with Norman Spinrad next time.

10:36.760 --> 10:44.560
