11:30.740 --> 11:34.600
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

11:50.160 --> 11:55.480
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

11:58.080 --> 11:59.800
And here are your hosts.

12:04.600 --> 12:13.080
This is Daryl Lane. And David Crews. Norman Spinrad's 1979 science fiction novel,
A World Between, signaled a change in his fiction. Spinrad's early work usually

12:13.080 --> 12:21.620
contain either subtle or overt criticism of various aspects of society. Bug Jack
Barron, The Men in the Jungle, and Agent of Chaos are good examples of this type.

12:22.000 --> 12:33.280
A World Between is also a socially oriented novel, but there's a different
element in it. Spinrad explains. I would say in general that up until, I guess A

12:33.280 --> 12:44.440
World Between, really, a lot of my stuff was kind of critical fiction, critical
of this, critical of existing societies, critical of various things that were

12:44.440 --> 12:55.360
going on. A World Between is meant as a utopian novel, really, in any kind of
way, and it's a prescriptive kind of book. It's more of a, instead of presenting

12:55.360 --> 13:04.680
critical images of other things, the idea is to create a more positive image of
a more positive kind of future. I think if you spend enough time criticizing

13:04.680 --> 13:17.240
what exists, at some point, you'll have some kind of moral obligation to present
something more positive and replace what you find negative.

13:21.900 --> 13:29.500
The setting for the novel is a fit one for a utopia. It takes place on the
planet Pacifica, a beautiful world of blue ocean and lush green islands that's

13:29.500 --> 13:36.820
been colonized by humans. Inhabitants of Pacifica live private lives in their
isolated islands. There are no large urban centers to cause pollution,

13:37.020 --> 13:44.260
overpopulation, or poverty. Even though they are physically isolated, the
Pacificans remain in close electronic contact with one another. They govern

13:44.260 --> 13:51.940
themselves, in fact, with a tight media web that allows them to vote immediately
on any issue of importance. But into this idyllic world comes two opposed

13:51.940 --> 14:00.320
political forces from Earth, bent on the ideological conquest of Pacifica. One
force is the Institute for Transcendental Science, a powerful organization whose

14:00.320 --> 14:11.700
goal is galactic unity under their control. They are extreme, and Spinrad says
they have two basic flaws. One is the unexamined, subtle male chauvinist bias of

14:11.700 --> 14:23.900
their culture. And the other one is the ultimate conviction that what they are
doing is the absolute most important thing in the universe, and that therefore

14:23.900 --> 14:31.540
they are morally entitled to run over other people's cultures and desires.

14:38.640 --> 14:48.440
The other force is the Femocrats, a militant women's liberation group that is
also an extreme. The struggle of these two groups for control of planets all

14:48.440 --> 14:55.900
across the galaxy is called the Pink and Blue War. It's clearly a male-female
conflict, and so far every planet the two sides have approached has ended up on

14:55.900 --> 15:04.540
one side or the other. But Pacifica is different. Spinrad's utopia is a stable
and intelligent one. The Pacificans reject both extremes and even change the

15:04.540 --> 15:13.140
minds of a few of the combatants. We asked Spinrad about reactions to the book.
How did women, for instance, respond to the Femocratic women's livers? The

15:13.140 --> 15:26.680
strange thing about the reaction to that book has been that a certain number of
men have reacted in a kind of male liberal guilt, male feminist kind of reaction

15:26.680 --> 15:36.140
against that. For the most part, women have liked the book. Women have
identified with it more than men. And actually, I even got one or two good

15:36.140 --> 15:44.840
reviews in feminist places. I think that's not quite what I expected, but that
seems to be the way it happened. I have not gotten heavy feminist flack from

15:44.840 --> 15:56.240
that. A little bit, but not much. Not much, because I think women who are
involved in feminism or have been or know women who are can recognize a certain

15:56.240 --> 16:05.220
aspect of the feminist movement in the Femocrats, whereas men who are trying to
show how liberated they are would not dream of admitting such a thing. A World

16:05.220 --> 16:09.200
Between, a different sort of book for Norman Spinrad, and we'll have more on him
tomorrow.

16:16.220 --> 16:24.060
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:24.060 --> 16:24.800
Odessa, Texas.

17:08.960 --> 17:12.840
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:28.520 --> 17:33.680
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

17:36.400 --> 17:37.980
And here are your hosts.

17:42.800 --> 17:51.700
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Norman Spinrad's most recent novel, Songs
from the Stars, was published by Simon & Schuster in 1980. The book describes a

17:51.700 --> 17:59.520
fragmented future society in a world devastated by nuclear war. This, of course,
is a typical Spinrad theme. But the novel also communicates the sense of wonder

17:59.520 --> 18:07.500
characteristic of good science fiction when it describes the marvels of contact
with an alien civilization. Society is split in two factions in Songs from the

18:07.500 --> 18:15.140
Stars. One faction is an Aquarian society which bans all technology, in fact,
anything having to do with science, since this was what was responsible for

18:15.140 --> 18:22.500
almost destroying the Earth. And the other faction are the black scientists who
keep technology alive and maintain an illicit smuggling operation with the

18:22.500 --> 18:31.980
Aquarian society. Spinrad talks about these opposed factions. It's a book
against duality. I mean, you have two fragmented societies. They're both...

18:34.780 --> 18:46.060
both are kind of like half-societies. The Aquarian society there is a very nice
thing that works, except it really only works because it accepts something from

18:46.060 --> 19:00.220
the black scientists which it doesn't want to admit that it's accepted. And the
black scientists are, again, another kind of absolutism which doesn't

19:00.220 --> 19:11.920
sell... It's a kind of a... It's a book about... about higher unity, I guess. As
usual, with Spinrad, the book's conflict reflects current social conditions. You

19:11.920 --> 19:19.480
know, it mirrors the present thing in our society where, on the one hand, you
have a great big space movement and people wanting to get into space and all the

19:19.480 --> 19:28.760
old people and all that stuff. On the other hand, you have a real atavistic neo
-Luddite movement, an anti-nuclear movement which is really kind of willfully

19:28.760 --> 19:35.780
ignorant of a lot of things. In a way, these are the two things that could bring
about the crash

19:39.620 --> 19:49.600
as well as what would survive it. So I think it's basically a book about... The
grand philosophical attempt in that book is to try and bridge the gap between

19:49.600 --> 20:01.680
science and reason and, you know, feeling, emotion, and mysticism. And to... You
know, to point to a higher unity between the two things and away from the false

20:01.680 --> 20:10.360
dichotomies and false dualisms would seem to be really destroying Western
civilization, as a law stated. The protagonist in the book is a laid-back

20:10.360 --> 20:17.940
Aquarian, Clear Blue Lou. Along with his girl and a scientist, he travels up to
a satellite circling the Earth. There, the three of them receive communication

20:17.940 --> 20:25.800
from some incredibly advanced alien civilizations in another part of the galaxy.
With the knowledge sent by the helpful aliens, it seems the humans will solve

20:25.800 --> 20:33.760
their own problems, unite, and start progressing toward the stars once more. We
asked Spinrad that if and when we contact an alien civilization is it likely

20:33.760 --> 20:43.780
they will be helpful rather than hostile? As I said in the book, I do believe
that any civilization that's going to last a million years, it's going to be a

20:43.780 --> 20:51.940
million years or whatever or even a hundred thousand years more advanced than us
that have been around that much longer and that much more advanced science. If

20:51.940 --> 21:00.760
it's going to survive to that length of its own history, it's got to solve it,
you know, it's got to be by that time philosophically and emotionally pretty

21:00.760 --> 21:10.060
together or long since it destroyed itself. I mean, we certainly will not
survive a million years of our own history if it continues as it has, you know,

21:10.780 --> 21:19.600
in order that any civilization that survives a million years of its own history
has had to have gotten its political, psychological, and philosophical act

21:19.600 --> 21:34.360
together. and I don't see why, you know, you know, and I do believe that if and
when we run into that kind of really advanced civilizations, that they will, if

21:34.360 --> 21:42.200
not be directly actively helpful, certainly will be benign and will not be
interested in either eating us or conquering our planet or blowing us up or

21:42.200 --> 21:49.280
anything like that. Songs from the Stars is a thoughtfully written book with a
theme, but it's also good, exciting science fiction.

21:56.680 --> 22:04.500
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

22:04.500 --> 22:05.240
Odessa, Texas.

