23:10.700 --> 23:15.920
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

23:18.640 --> 23:20.220
And here are your hosts.

23:24.320 --> 23:32.960
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. James P. Hogan's latest novel, Voyage from
Yesteryear, is a fascinating blend of computers, space exploration, and genetic

23:32.960 --> 23:39.760
engineering. It's about a robot probe that discovers a habitable planet ten
light years from Earth, but it's different than the usual probe imagined by

23:39.760 --> 23:48.700
science fiction authors. Right. This one is equipped to manufacture human
beings. Hogan explains. We read a lot of stories about starships that go on long

23:48.700 --> 23:58.500
voyages that take maybe centuries, and inevitably they've got frozen bodies or
bodies in suspended animation or something like that. But when you think about

23:58.500 --> 24:05.900
it, it seems rather an inefficient way to say, you know, if they're not doing
anything, the machines can fly the ship, the computers can get it there. The

24:05.900 --> 24:15.400
people aren't doing anything about it except, you know, just lying there
freezing. So, you know, why not let the machines fly the ship and make the

24:15.400 --> 24:25.320
people when you get there? But if we look at the progress made in molecular
biology and genetic engineering in the last couple of decades, we already

24:25.320 --> 24:34.740
manufacture quite complex organic molecules to specifications, such as drugs and
certainly antithetics. If we just extrapolate that a little further, who's to

24:34.740 --> 24:43.420
say you couldn't make a complete set of human DNA? In other words, instead of
sending bodies and all the support equipment to freeze them and taking up all

24:43.420 --> 24:48.500
the space, why not just store

24:48.500 --> 25:01.720
all the genetic information necessary to make people electronically in the
computers and create them when you have found a planet that the instruments say

25:01.720 --> 25:10.120
they could survive on? So the computers make a race of humans, raise them, and
place them on the planet. It sounds a bit mechanical, a little inhuman perhaps,

25:10.480 --> 25:24.700
but Hogan thinks it could work out beautifully. So here is the interesting
possibility of a race that evolves from a first generation of embryos that were

25:24.700 --> 25:35.680
created and nurtured and raised by computers and robots, a machine-raised race.
And when you think about it, the relationship between the children and the

25:35.680 --> 25:45.900
machines does not really have to be a cold and sinister one at all. It could be
quite a charming and amusing one. The interesting thoughts that the book starts

25:45.900 --> 25:52.700
to play with is, here is a race of kids that are being raised by some

25:52.700 --> 26:05.060
very rational, direct, down-to-earth entities who don't double-talk or deceive
or have all these layers of human game-playing that we have to contend with. And

26:05.060 --> 26:10.960
they're being raised completely without

26:10.960 --> 26:23.440
any exposure to the conditioning of conditioned adults with their prejudices and
hatreds and taboos and a lot of the other nonsenses that make life so

26:23.440 --> 26:32.860
complicated in our society. As you might expect, these machine-raised humans are
eventually contacted by humans from Earth. Let's imagine that a mission from

26:32.860 --> 26:34.300
Earth eventually shows up.

26:37.420 --> 26:47.120
Virtually, you know, a big mission. This is usually a 20-year voyage, maybe. So
we're talking about a spaceship that maybe houses 20,000 people, virtually a

26:47.120 --> 26:56.420
space colony with engines, with its government, its military, its church
organisations, its commercial institutions, the whole of society in miniature

26:56.420 --> 27:12.140
with its time-proved mechanisms for controlling and subordinating a population,
which traditionally a ruling elite through history has imposed itself by

27:12.140 --> 27:23.420
restricting the flow of wealth and by offering protection either from real or
imagined threats. And so what happens when a race of machine-raised people

27:23.420 --> 27:32.180
eventually collides with a race of people-raised people? And that's really what
the story's all about. Voyage from Yesteryear will be out in paperback at the

27:32.180 --> 27:35.720
end of July. Next week we'll have a series of shows on the works of James B.
Hogan.

27:42.640 --> 27:50.300
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

